---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical}>

<Fragment slot="head-scripts">
  {schemaJsons.map((schema) => (<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(schema)} />))}
</Fragment>

<ServiceHero
  eyebrow="SAFETY first · Mica Waveguide Cover · Cavity Damage · Foreign Metal"
  title="Microwave Sparking, Arcing Inside"
  subtitle="STOP USE IMMEDIATELY. Unplug. Real kitchen fire risk on next cycle. Use toaster oven or stovetop until we arrive. $89 diagnostic across LA, OC, Ventura. (424) 325-0520"
  heroImageTitle="Microwave Sparking Repair"
  showBranches={true}
/>

<section class="safety-section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="safety-eyebrow">⚠️ Safety first</p>
    <h2 class="safety-title">Stop using the microwave immediately. Unplug. Do not run empty.</h2>
    <p>Sparking or arcing inside a microwave can cause a kitchen fire. We've seen the damage progress from "small spark" to "burnt cavity" in one or two more uses. The plastic edge bonding around the mica waveguide cover ignites at temperatures sparking can reach. The 2 to 3 days waiting for an appointment, leave the unit unplugged. Use a toaster oven or stovetop for heating.</p>
    <p>Call us: <a href={phoneHref}>{phone}</a>. Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura. $89 diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Most common cause: mica waveguide cover</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Year 6 to 10. Customers often call it "the wax paper thing".</h2>

    <p>The waveguide cover is a small mica panel on the right side or top of the microwave cavity. Mica is a heat-resistant mineral; customers often misidentify it as wax paper, cardboard, or plastic. It covers the opening where microwaves enter the cavity from the magnetron, protecting the magnetron from food splatter.</p>

    <p>Failure pattern: food splashes (cheese, melted soup, sauce, oil) bake onto the mica over years of use. Year 6 to 10 typical for a hard-use household. Eventually the baked-on residue carbonizes and conducts electricity, which is when arcing begins.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Brown or black burn = replace</h3>
    <p>If the waveguide cover has visible brown or black burn marks, crusty carbon residue, or charred edges, replacement is required. Continued use ignites the carbon and propagates damage to the magnetron, cavity coating, or surrounding plastic.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">White discoloration = wipe and assess</h3>
    <p>White discoloration is typically food residue or mineral deposit from steam, not burn damage. Wipe gently with a damp cloth (no abrasive cleaners; mica is delicate). If the surface cleans up to its original off-white color, the cover is still functional and arcing was something else (foreign metal, cavity damage, magnetron). If the white residue won't wipe off or there's any brown crust mixed in, replacement is the call.</p>

    <p>Replacement: $40 to $120 part plus $89 diagnostic plus 15-minute install. Common sparking-microwave repair, often $169 to $209 total resolved.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Customer-side: metal object inside</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Foreign metal arcs immediately. No mechanical fault.</h2>

    <p>Aluminum foil scraps, twist-ties, decorative china with metallic gold or silver trim, all arc immediately when the microwave runs. Customer-side error, the unit itself isn't malfunctioning. $89 diagnostic confirms the cavity is undamaged from the arcing event (sometimes the foil scratched the cavity paint exposing metal underneath, which causes future sparking even after the foil is removed; see next section).</p>

    <p>If cavity is intact post-arcing event, no parts billed, just the diagnostic. We educate on the metal-and-microwave rule and confirm the unit is safe to operate.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Damaged interior cavity paint</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Exposed metal arcs. Cavity coating repair or replace conversation.</h2>

    <p>The interior cavity is steel coated with paint. When the paint is chipped, scratched (often from a metal object scrape or cleaning with abrasive pads), or peeled, the exposed metal underneath arcs during normal operation. Symptom: small sparks emerge from a specific spot, often where a previous metal incident or cleaning damage occurred.</p>

    <p>Cavity coating repair: $120 to $280 mid-tier. Microwave-rated paint applied to the damaged area, cured, returned to service. Effective on small areas. Large or multiple damage zones can't be coated effectively, replacement is the call.</p>

    <p>Pro-style or built-in exception: Wolf, Miele, Thermador, GE Monogram, Sharp drawer cavity coating repair always justified given $1,500 to $4,000 replacement cost.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Magnetron dome failure (rare, dangerous)</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Internal magnetron damage causes arcing visible through the waveguide.</h2>

    <p>Rare failure mode, but it happens. The magnetron itself develops internal damage (sometimes from running empty, sometimes from voltage events) and produces visible arcing inside its dome. Sparks may appear to come from the waveguide cover side but originate behind it. Diagnostic: remove waveguide cover, inspect magnetron face. Carbon deposits or visible damage on the magnetron antenna mean replacement.</p>

    <p>Magnetron replacement same as on the not-heating page: $260 to $440 mid-tier, $440 to $680 pro-style/built-in.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Recent jobs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Real diagnostic stories from the last few weeks.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Composite examples; model numbers, ages, and prices are accurate to typical scope.</p>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Pasadena · GE Profile OTR microwave, 7 years old</h3>
      <p>Owner reported sparks from the right side, ran one more cycle to test, sparks got worse. Called us. Diagnosed: mica waveguide cover with brown soup-splatter burn (3 inch x 1 inch carbonized area). Replaced cover, ran 2-minute test cycle with cup of water. Total: $89 plus $80 cover plus 20 minutes = $169.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>West Hollywood · Whirlpool countertop microwave, 4 years old</h3>
      <p>Owner reported sparking. On-site inspection: foil scrap on the turntable from a takeout container that customer hadn't noticed. Cavity intact (foil arcs were brief enough that paint wasn't damaged). Removed foil, tested unit with cup of water for 2 minutes. No further arcing. Total: $89 diagnostic only, customer-side education.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Beverly Hills · Wolf MWD30 drawer microwave, 9 years old</h3>
      <p>Mica waveguide cover with extensive black burn, plus a small area of cavity coating damage where the burn had reached the wall. Replaced waveguide cover, applied cavity coating to the damaged spot, cured. Pro-style drawer at $2,800+ replacement, repair the obvious call. Total: $89 plus $260 parts plus 1 hour = $340.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Marina del Rey · GE Profile OTR microwave, 11 years old</h3>
      <p>Customer reported persistent sparking; previous shop replaced waveguide cover but sparking returned within a week. Diagnosed: extensive cavity coating damage across the back wall (year-11 unit, paint was already failing in multiple spots). Mid-tier OTR at year 11 with this scope of damage doesn't repair-pencil. Quoted $400+ for cavity repair on a $400 to $600 replacement-OTR-installed scenario; customer chose replacement. Total: $89 diagnostic, honest replace-conversation answer.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="story">
      <h3>Calabasas · Miele M Touch built-in microwave, 8 years old</h3>
      <p>Mica waveguide cover with white discoloration, customer assumed burn damage. Wipe-down test at the diagnostic: discoloration cleaned up to original off-white. Cover was functional. Diagnosed: actual sparking source was a small foil fragment from a Miele test pan that had caught on the cavity wall. Removed foil, confirmed waveguide cover usable, no replacement needed. Total: $89 diagnostic only. Customer relieved at the wipe-and-assess outcome.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">06 · Repair vs replace by tier</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Cavity damage drives the decision.</h2>

    <p><strong>Countertop ($150 to $300):</strong> waveguide cover replacement always worth it ($169 to $209). Cavity coating damage on year-10+ unit tilts toward replacement; repair cost $200 to $400 on a $150 to $300 unit doesn't pencil.</p>

    <p><strong>OTR ($300 to $700 unit installed):</strong> waveguide cover always. Cavity coating repair through year 8 to 9. Year-11+ extensive cavity damage is replace conversation.</p>

    <p><strong>Pro-style or built-in (Wolf, Miele, Thermador, GE Monogram, Sharp drawer):</strong> all cavity work justified through year 15+. Replacement cost ($1,500 to $4,000) plus cabinet integration complexity makes repair the obvious call.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">07 · LA fire safety</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Sparking microwave is a real kitchen fire risk. Don't run it.</h2>

    <p>We've seen kitchen fires that started in a sparking microwave. The plastic edge bonding around the mica waveguide cover, the plastic interior touchpoints, the cabinet plastic surrounding an OTR unit, all combust at temperatures sparking can reach during a 2-minute heating cycle. The 2 to 3 days waiting for our appointment, leave the unit unplugged. Use a toaster oven, stovetop, or rice cooker for heating in the meantime.</p>

    <p>If you've already had a fire start (visible flame, smoke from the cabinet), evacuate, call 911, then call us after the fire department clears the scene. We'll assess whether the unit is repairable or replace-only.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">08 · Pricing</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What microwave-sparking repair actually costs.</h2>

    <table class="price-table">
      <thead>
        <tr><th>Service</th><th>Cost</th></tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Diagnostic visit (includes safety assessment)</td><td>$89, waived with repair</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Foreign metal removal + assessment (no parts)</td><td>$89 diagnostic only</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Mica waveguide cover replacement</td><td>$169 to $209 typical ($89 dx plus $40 to $120 cover)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Cavity coating repair (small area)</td><td>$210 to $370 ($89 dx plus $120 to $280 coating)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Combined waveguide plus cavity coating</td><td>$280 to $440</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Magnetron replacement (if dome damage)</td><td>$350 to $720 (mid-tier to pro-style)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Multi-component repair (year 9+ pro-style)</td><td>$580 to $900</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Warranty</td><td>90 days parts and labor</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <p class="price-note">Residential $89 diagnostic, applied toward repair. About 15% of sparking calls are foreign metal removal with no parts billed.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">09 · Why us</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Six reasons.</h2>

    <ul class="why-list">
      <li><strong>Safety-first protocol.</strong> Diagnostic includes safe-to-operate assessment, not just parts quoting.</li>
      <li><strong>Wipe-and-assess on white waveguide discoloration.</strong> Don't replace covers that are still functional.</li>
      <li><strong>Cavity coating repair capability.</strong> Microwave-rated paint, cured properly, effective on small damage zones.</li>
      <li><strong>Pro-style cavity work.</strong> Wolf, Miele, Thermador, GE Monogram, Sharp drawer always repair-justified.</li>
      <li><strong>BHGS #A49573 plus EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410).</strong> Verifiable.</li>
      <li><strong>Same-day across LA, OC, Ventura.</strong> 24/7 phones, no emergency surcharge. Sparking microwave is a same-day priority for us.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>Sister sub-services: <a href="/services/microwave-repair/not-heating/">not heating</a>, <a href="/services/microwave-repair/no-power/">no power</a>, <a href="/services/microwave-repair/plate-not-rotating/">plate not rotating</a>. Parent: <a href="/services/microwave-repair/">microwave repair</a>. Credentials: <a href="/credentials/licensed/">BHGS license</a>, <a href="/credentials/epa-certified/">EPA 608</a>.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">10 · FAQ</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Microwave sparking, common questions.</h2>

    <div class="faq-list">
      {faqs.map((f) => (
        <details class="faq-item">
          <summary>{f.q}</summary>
          <p>{f.a}</p>
        </details>
